  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering, including:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verify customer identities\n- Conduct background checks\n- Monitor suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- File Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Report large cash transactions\n- Disclose potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Develop internal policies and procedures\n- Train employees on detecting suspicious activities\n- Maintain transaction records\n\n4. Risk assessment\n- Identify high-risk customers and transactions\n- Implement enhanced due diligence for risky accounts\n\n5. Regulatory compliance\n- Follow laws like the Bank Secrecy Act\n- Cooperate with law enforcement investigations\n- Face potential penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. International standards\n- Adhere to Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Collaborate across jurisdictions to prevent money laundering\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant legal and financial consequences for financial institutions.",
